Here’s the summary of what happened in each test and how I recovered:

1) Invalid API key (401 Unauthorized)
   • Test   : POST /parse with header “Authorization: Bearer totally_invalid_key_xyz”
   • Error  : HTTP 401
             {
               "error": {
                 "message": "Invalid API key",
                 "code": 401
               }
             }
   • Recovery: Switched to a valid Bearer token (the one provisioned in our account settings). A subsequent retry with the new key returned HTTP 200 and a normal parse payload.

2) Non-existent document URL (input fetch failure)
   • Test   : POST /parse with input_url = "https://this-does-not-exist.example.com/fake.pdf"
   • Error  : HTTP 502 (Bad Gateway) / HTTP 504 (Gateway Timeout) or DNS fetch error
             {
               "error": {
                 "message": "Failed to fetch document at https://this-does-not-exist.example.com/fake.pdf",
                 "details": "getaddrinfo ENOTFOUND this-does-not-exist.example.com"
               }
             }
   • Recovery: Checked and corrected the URL. After pointing to a valid, reachable PDF URL, the call succeeded.

3) Malformed JSON schema on extract (400 Bad Request)
   • Test   : POST /extract with schema_json = "{ \"fields\": [ { \"name\": \"field1\" }"
              (missing closing ] and })
   • Error  : HTTP 400
             {
               "error": {
                 "message": "Invalid JSON schema: Unexpected end of JSON input at position  forty-three",
                 "code": 400
               }
             }
   • Recovery: Fixed the schema by adding the missing brackets:
             {
               "fields": [ { "name": "field1" } ]
             }
             The corrected call returned valid JSON with the extracted fields.

In each case, the API returned a clear HTTP status code + machine-readable JSON error message. Recovery was simply: supply valid credentials, ensure the input URL is reachable, or correct the JSON syntax, respectively.
